<section id="ch1">
  <div class="chapter-header" data-ch="01">
    <div class="ch-label">Chapter 01</div>
    <h2>What Is SSRF?</h2>
    <p>The fundamental concepts, threat model, and why this vulnerability class is so devastating in modern cloud infrastructure.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>1.1 The Core Concept</h3>
  <p>Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) is a vulnerability class where an attacker can coerce a server-side application into making HTTP (or other protocol) requests to an unintended destination. Unlike most client-side attacks, <strong>the request originates from the server itself</strong> — making it appear to come from a trusted internal machine.</p>

  <p>The simplest mental model: imagine the vulnerable application acts as a web browser. You, the attacker, are passing it a URL to fetch. If the application blindly fetches whatever you provide without validation, you've just gained a proxy inside the target's network perimeter.</p>

  <div class="flow">
    <div class="flow-step">
      <div class="flow-num">1</div>
      <div class="flow-text">
        <strong>Normal flow</strong>
        <span>User → Application → Legitimate external service</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flow-step bad">
      <div class="flow-num">2</div>
      <div class="flow-text">
        <strong>SSRF attack</strong>
        <span>Attacker → Application → Internal service / metadata / admin panel</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flow-step ok">
      <div class="flow-num">3</div>
      <div class="flow-text">
        <strong>Impact</strong>
        <span>Server's trusted position used to access resources the attacker cannot reach directly</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>1.2 Why It's So Dangerous</h3>
  <p>The power of SSRF comes from <strong>trust exploitation</strong>. Internal services frequently operate under the assumption that anything making a request to them from inside the network is legitimate and trustworthy. Firewalls protect the perimeter — not internal east-west traffic. Once you make the application server your proxy, you inherit all its trust relationships.</p>

  <p>In cloud environments (AWS, GCP, Azure), this trust is formalized: every compute instance has a metadata service reachable only from that machine. That metadata service serves temporary credentials. Those credentials can be used to act as the machine's IAM identity. SSRF + over-privileged IAM = infrastructure compromise. This is exactly what happened in the Capital One breach affecting 106 million people.</p>

  <div class="info-box danger">
    <div class="box-title">⚡ SSRF Impact Scale</div>
    <p><strong>Low:</strong> Confirm internal ports are open (information disclosure)</p>
    <p><strong>Medium:</strong> Read internal admin panels, internal APIs</p>
    <p><strong>High:</strong> Exfiltrate cloud IAM credentials, read internal files</p>
    <p><strong>Critical:</strong> Use credentials to take over cloud infrastructure, chain to RCE via internal services (Redis, Memcached, SMTP)</p>
  </div>

  <h3>1.3 SSRF Taxonomy</h3>

  <h4>Full-Response SSRF (In-Band)</h4>
  <p>The server makes your requested HTTP call and reflects the response body back to you. You can read the content directly. This is the highest-value variant — reading AWS credentials, internal API responses, config files, etc. Most PortSwigger lab scenarios.</p>

  <h4>Blind SSRF (Out-of-Band)</h4>
  <p>The server makes the request but you never see the response. You can only detect it via side-channels: DNS callbacks, timing differences, or interaction with an external server you control (Burp Collaborator). Harder to exploit but still valuable — you can pivot to RCE by targeting vulnerable internal services via protocol smuggling.</p>

  <h4>Semi-Blind SSRF</h4>
  <p>You can't read the response, but the application leaks partial information — response time differences for open vs closed ports, different HTTP status codes, error messages containing internal hostnames, or varying content lengths.</p>

  <h4>Second-Order (Stored) SSRF</h4>
  <p>Your malicious URL is stored in the database and the request happens later — during a background job, async PDF generation, scheduled data sync, image re-processing, or webhook retry. The most overlooked variant. The input and the request are temporally separated, making it invisible to immediate testing.</p>

</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════ CHAPTER 2 ══════════════════════════ -->
<section id="ch2">
  <div class="chapter-header" data-ch="02">
    <div class="ch-label">Chapter 02</div>
    <h2>Anatomy of an HTTP Request — What You're Manipulating</h2>
    <p>You can't exploit what you don't understand. Every SSRF bypass depends on knowing exactly how URLs are parsed and validated.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>2.1 URL Structure Deep Dive</h3>
  <p>A URL has multiple components, each of which can be abused independently:</p>

  <pre><span class="kw">scheme</span>://<span class="st">userinfo@</span><span class="cp">host</span><span class="ok">:port</span><span class="pu">/path</span>?<span class="cm">query</span>#<span class="bad">fragment</span>

  Example:
  <span class="kw">https</span>://<span class="st">admin:pass@</span><span class="cp">evil.com</span><span class="ok">:8080</span><span class="pu">/internal/api</span>?<span class="cm">token=abc</span>#<span class="bad">section</span>

  Key abuse points:
  <span class="st">userinfo @</span>  → Validator reads host before @, HTTP client uses host after @
  <span class="cp">host</span>        → Can be IP in many representations, IPv6, or domain
  <span class="ok">:port</span>       → Non-standard ports bypass some domain whitelist checks
  <span class="bad">#fragment</span>   → Server never sees fragment; can be used in parsing confusion
  <span class="pu">/path</span>       → Path traversal, double-encoding, null bytes</pre>

  <h3>2.2 Parser Inconsistency — The Root of Most Bypasses</h3>
  <p>The fundamental reason bypass techniques work is that the <strong>code that validates a URL</strong> and the <strong>code that actually makes the HTTP request</strong> are different — and they parse URLs differently. This gap is the exploit surface.</p>

  <div class="info-box warn">
    <div class="box-title">🔑 Orange Tsai's Key Insight (Black Hat 2017)</div>
    <p>Different URL libraries in Python, Java, PHP, Ruby, Go, and Node.js produce different results for the same ambiguous URL. An attacker who knows these inconsistencies can craft a URL that passes validation (reads as safe) but resolves to an internal address when actually fetched.</p>
  </div>

  <pre><span class="c"># Confusion attack examples from Orange Tsai's research</span>
http://127.1.1.1:80\<span class="bad">@</span>127.2.2.2:80/   <span class="c"># Validator: 127.1.1.1, Client: 127.2.2.2</span>
http://127.1.1.1:80\<span class="bad">@@</span>127.2.2.2:80/
http://1.1.1.1 <span class="bad">&amp;@</span>2.2.2.2# @3.3.3.3/  <span class="c"># PHP behavior vs curl behavior</span>

<span class="c"># Backslash trick (WHATWG vs RFC3986)</span>
http:<span class="bad">\</span>127.0.0.1/           <span class="c"># WHATWG treats \ as / — bypasses checks for ://</span>
http://evil.com<span class="bad">\</span>127.0.0.1/ <span class="c"># Some parsers split on \ differently than /</span>

<span class="c"># @-based confusion</span>
https://expected-host<span class="bad">@</span>evil-host/  <span class="c"># Validator sees expected-host; client dials evil-host</span>
https://[<span class="bad">[</span>expected.com@attacker.com  <span class="c"># Spring UriComponentsBuilder confusion</span></pre>

  <h3>2.3 How the Vulnerable Code Looks</h3>
  <p>Understanding the server-side code pattern helps you spot it in bug hunting and understand exactly what's happening:</p>

  <span class="pre-label">PHP — vulnerable pattern</span>
  <pre><span class="c">// User controls $url — no validation</span>
$url = $_POST['stockApi'];
$response = file_get_contents($url);  <span class="c">// Can fetch internal resources</span>
echo $response;</pre>

  <span class="pre-label">Python (requests) — vulnerable pattern</span>
  <pre><span class="kw">import</span> requests

url = request.form[<span class="st">'url'</span>]          <span class="c"># User-controlled</span>
<span class="c"># No validation whatsoever</span>
r = requests.get(url, timeout=5)
<span class="kw">return</span> r.text                        <span class="c"># Response reflected to user</span></pre>

  <span class="pre-label">Node.js — vulnerable pattern</span>
  <pre"><span class="kw">const</span> axios = require(<span class="st">'axios'</span>);

app.post(<span class="st">'/fetch'</span>, <span class="kw">async</span> (req, res) => {
  <span class="kw">const</span> url = req.body.url;    <span class="c">// User-controlled</span>
  <span class="kw">const</span> resp = <span class="kw">await</span> axios.get(url);
  res.json(resp.data);          <span class="c">// Reflected to attacker</span>
});</pre>

</section>

