<section id="ch3">
  <div class="chapter-header" data-ch="03">
    <div class="ch-label">Chapter 03</div>
    <h2>Finding the Attack Surface</h2>
    <p>Where SSRF hides in real applications — and how to uncover it systematically.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>3.1 Obvious Entry Points (Check First)</h3>

  <p>These parameter names are classic SSRF candidates. Always test them immediately:</p>

  <div class="wordlist">
    <code>url=</code><code>uri=</code><code>path=</code><code>dest=</code><code>redirect=</code>
    <code>next=</code><code>target=</code><code>link=</code><code>source=</code><code>image=</code>
    <code>image_url=</code><code>avatar=</code><code>callback=</code><code>return=</code><code>r=</code>
    <code>proxy=</code><code>feed=</code><code>data=</code><code>reference=</code><code>site=</code>
    <code>webhook=</code><code>endpoint=</code><code>host=</code><code>page=</code><code>file=</code>
    <code>document=</code><code>import=</code><code>fetch=</code><code>resource=</code><code>from=</code>
    <code>to=</code><code>out=</code><code>view=</code><code>show=</code><code>open=</code>
    <code>return_url=</code><code>redirect_url=</code><code>continue=</code><code>go=</code>
  </div>

  <div class="info-box tip">
    <div class="box-title">💡 Pro Tip: grep JS files</div>
    <p>Run: <code>grep -r "fetch\|axios\|http\.get\|file_get_contents\|urllib\|requests\.get" --include="*.js"</code> on downloaded JS bundles. Also grep for parameter names above in minified JS to find hidden endpoints feeding URLs to backend.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>3.2 Feature Categories That Always Contain SSRF</h3>

  <div class="method-grid">
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="m-icon">🔗</div>
      <div class="m-title">URL Preview / Link Unfurl</div>
      <div class="m-desc">Chat apps, Slack-style tools, social platforms that fetch OG metadata. The fetch happens server-side. Always test with Collaborator URL.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="m-icon">📎</div>
      <div class="m-title">Import from URL</div>
      <div class="m-desc">Dropbox/GDrive/OneDrive import, "add from web", import CSV from URL, document import. These fetch user-controlled URLs.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="m-icon">🖼️</div>
      <div class="m-title">Avatar / Image by URL</div>
      <div class="m-desc">Profile avatar via external URL. The server downloads and re-hosts the image. Points for testing: the download endpoint, not the display.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="m-icon">📄</div>
      <div class="m-title">PDF / Screenshot Generation</div>
      <div class="m-desc">Any feature rendering HTML to PDF (wkhtmltopdf, puppeteer, PhantomJS). Inject &lt;iframe src="http://169.254.169.254/..."&gt; or &lt;img src=...&gt; in user-controlled content.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="m-icon">🔔</div>
      <div class="m-title">Webhooks / Callbacks</div>
      <div class="m-desc">Payment providers, CI/CD triggers, Zapier-style integrations. You supply the callback URL. Test redirects and SSRF directly.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="m-icon">🔐</div>
      <div class="m-title">SSO / OAuth Config</div>
      <div class="m-desc">SAML metadata URL, OIDC discovery endpoint, custom identity provider URL. The server fetches these URLs to configure SSO.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="m-icon">📡</div>
      <div class="m-title">RSS / Feed Aggregation</div>
      <div class="m-desc">Any "subscribe to RSS feed" or "add data source" feature. The URL is fetched server-side.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="m-icon">📊</div>
      <div class="m-title">Stock / Price Checkers</div>
      <div class="m-desc">Classic PortSwigger lab pattern. stockApi parameter containing a full URL is trivially exploitable.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="method-card">
      <div class="m-icon">🖥️</div>
      <div class="m-title">HTTP Headers</div>
      <div class="m-desc">X-Forwarded-For, Referer, Origin, Host, X-Real-IP, Client-IP. Analytics/logging code that fetches the Referer URL is a classic blind SSRF source.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>3.3 Hidden / Non-Obvious Sources</h3>

  <h4>SVG / XML File Uploads</h4>
  <p>SVG files support external entity references and embedded images. An SVG with <code>&lt;image href="http://169.254.169.254/"&gt;</code> can trigger server-side fetching when the SVG is processed or rendered server-side.</p>

  <pre><span class="c">&lt;!-- Malicious SVG for SSRF --&gt;</span>
&lt;<span class="kw">svg</span> xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
     xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"&gt;
  &lt;<span class="kw">image</span> xlink:href=<span class="st">"http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/"</span> /&gt;
&lt;/svg&gt;</pre>

  <h4>Office Documents (XLSX, DOCX)</h4>
  <p>Microsoft Office docs are ZIP archives containing XML. The XML can contain external references. When the server processes these for preview/conversion, the external entities are fetched:</p>

  <pre><span class="c">&lt;!-- Inside word/_rels/document.xml.rels --&gt;</span>
&lt;Relationship Id=<span class="st">"rId1"</span> Type=<span class="st">"..."</span>
  Target=<span class="bad">"http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/"</span>
  TargetMode=<span class="st">"External"</span>/&gt;

<span class="c">&lt;!-- Excel WEBSERVICE function --&gt;</span>
=WEBSERVICE(<span class="st">"http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/"</span>)</pre>

  <h4>FFmpeg / Video Processing</h4>
  <p>FFmpeg supports HLS playlists which can reference external files. If a target allows video upload and uses FFmpeg for processing, a malicious HLS playlist can trigger SSRF.</p>

  <h4>Indirect / Second-Order SSRF</h4>
  <p>Submit a URL to a profile field, report template, notification setting, or data import. The server stores it. Later, a background job processes it and makes the HTTP request. You won't see the effect immediately — use Burp Collaborator and wait, or check the application's behavior on a time delay.</p>

</section>

