<section id="ch9">
  <div class="chapter-header" data-ch="09">
    <div class="ch-label">Chapter 09</div>
    <h2>Real-World Bug Bounty Reports</h2>
    <p>Actual disclosed reports — attack chains, PoCs, bounties, and lessons for your own hunting.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="report-card">
    <div class="r-header">
      <div>
        <div class="r-company">HackerOne — PDF Generator SSRF</div>
        <span class="r-badge r-critical">CRITICAL · CVSS 10.0</span>
      </div>
      <div class="r-bounty">$25,000</div>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Report #2262382 | Researcher: @hackersight (mega7) | Fixed in &lt;24 hours</strong></p>
    <p>The analytics report PDF generator passed a user-controlled template value (<code>element[:template]</code>) directly into a PDF rendering library without sanitization. The library interpreted HTML in the template value, and an injected <code>&lt;iframe src="http://169.254.169.254/..."&gt;</code> caused the PDF renderer (wkhtmltopdf-style) to make a server-side request to the AWS metadata endpoint.</p>
    <div class="r-steps">
      <strong>Attack chain:</strong>
      <ol class="r-steps">
        <li>Go to HackerOne Analytics → PDF Report generation</li>
        <li>Find a template/element field that accepts custom HTML content</li>
        <li>Inject: <code>&lt;iframe src="http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;</code></li>
        <li>Generate the PDF — the renderer fetches the iframe src server-side</li>
        <li>The PDF contains the AWS credential response embedded in it</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
    <div class="info-box bounty" style="margin-top:14px;">
      <div class="box-title">💡 Lesson</div>
      <p>PDF generators are one of the highest-value SSRF targets. Any feature that renders user-controlled HTML server-side to produce a PDF is a candidate. Try: &lt;img src="..."&gt;, &lt;iframe&gt;, &lt;script src="..."&gt;, CSS url() properties, &lt;link href="..."&gt;.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="report-card">
    <div class="r-header">
      <div>
        <div class="r-company">Omise — Webhook SSRF via 303 Redirect</div>
        <span class="r-badge r-critical">CRITICAL</span>
      </div>
      <div class="r-bounty">Paid</div>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Report #508459 | Researcher: @honoki</strong></p>
    <p>Omise's webhook system blocked most redirects but had a bypass: HTTP 303 See Other status codes were followed. By hosting a server that returned 303 to the AWS metadata endpoint, the researcher caused the Omise webhook handler to fetch <code>http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/aws-opsworks-ec2-role</code> and expose AWS private keys.</p>
    <div class="r-steps">
      <strong>Attack chain:</strong>
      <ol class="r-steps">
        <li>Register a webhook URL pointing to attacker-controlled PHP server</li>
        <li>PHP returns: <code>header('Location: http://169.254.169.254/...', TRUE, 303);</code></li>
        <li>Omise's webhook handler follows the 303 redirect (unlike 301/302)</li>
        <li>AWS metadata returned to attacker via webhook response capture</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
    <div class="info-box bounty" style="margin-top:14px;">
      <div class="box-title">💡 Lesson</div>
      <p>When testing webhooks/callbacks, always try all redirect codes (301, 302, 303, 307, 308) — filters often block some but not all. 303 and 307 are especially worth testing. Host your own redirect server with each code type.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="report-card">
    <div class="r-header">
      <div>
        <div class="r-company">Dropbox (via HelloSign) — File Import SSRF</div>
        <span class="r-badge r-high">HIGH</span>
      </div>
      <div class="r-bounty">$4,913</div>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Researcher: @ehsayaan | Platform: HackerOne</strong></p>
    <p>HelloSign (Dropbox) had an "Import from Dropbox" feature with a <code>file_reference</code> parameter. Direct SSRF was blocked, but a 303 redirect bypass (same technique as Omise above) worked. The researcher retrieved full AWS metadata including AccessKeyId and temporary credentials.</p>
    <div class="r-steps">
      <strong>Attack chain:</strong>
      <ol class="r-steps">
        <li>Intercept the "Import document" request — find <code>file_reference</code> parameter</li>
        <li>Change value to Burp Collaborator URL → 404 (SSRF protection active)</li>
        <li>Tried http://127.0.0.1 → blocked. Gave up initially.</li>
        <li>Researched HackerOne Hacktivity → found 303 redirect bypass report #247680</li>
        <li>Hosted PHP server returning 303 → metadata endpoint</li>
        <li>Retrieved AWS Instance Metadata including IAM credentials</li>
        <li>Dropbox verified, fixed, and paid $4,913</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="report-card">
    <div class="r-header">
      <div>
        <div class="r-company">U.S. Department of Defense — download-url SSRF</div>
        <span class="r-badge r-critical">CRITICAL</span>
      </div>
      <div class="r-bounty">Paid (DoD VDP)</div>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Report #1624140 | Researcher: @rohsec</strong></p>
    <p>A DoD application exposed <code>/api/v1/download-url?url=</code> — a trivially obvious SSRF parameter. The url parameter was not validated, allowing direct access to AWS metadata service. The application ran on AWS EC2, so the metadata IP was accessible.</p>
    <pre>GET /api/v1/download-url?<span class="bad">url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/</span>
Host: [REDACTED DOD SYSTEM]</pre>
    <div class="info-box bounty" style="margin-top:14px;">
      <div class="box-title">💡 Lesson</div>
      <p>Endpoints named "download", "fetch", "proxy", "preview" with a url= parameter are almost always SSRF. These are often forgotten API endpoints that missed the security review cycle. Wordlist scan API paths for these patterns.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="report-card">
    <div class="r-header">
      <div>
        <div class="r-company">LarkSuite — Wiki Import SSRF via File Upload</div>
        <span class="r-badge r-critical">CRITICAL</span>
      </div>
      <div class="r-bounty">Critical Bounty Paid</div>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Researcher: @SirLeeroyJenkins | Platform: HackerOne</strong></p>
    <p>Lark's Wiki feature allowed importing content from 4 document types. After trying XXE via Office document XML (which failed), the researcher focused on a web-import feature. By submitting a URL that pointed to an attacker-controlled redirect server, they bypassed Lark's SSRF protections and achieved full read of AWS metadata.</p>
    <div class="r-steps">
      <strong>Key insight from the researcher:</strong>
      <ol class="r-steps">
        <li>"Deep dive the application" — learn every feature inside out</li>
        <li>File upload features involve server-side processing → always test for SSRF</li>
        <li>Office documents (ZIP+XML) are a viable XXE/SSRF vector when server processes them</li>
        <li>When direct SSRF is blocked, look for redirect chain bypass</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="report-card" style="border-left-color: var(--accent2);">
    <div class="r-header">
      <div>
        <div class="r-company">Capital One — The $80M SSRF Breach (Not Bounty)</div>
        <span class="r-badge r-critical">CRITICAL — 106 MILLION AFFECTED</span>
      </div>
      <div class="r-bounty">$80M Fine</div>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Attacker: Paige Thompson (ex-AWS engineer) | 2019</strong></p>
    <p>The most consequential SSRF attack in history. Thompson built a scanning tool to identify AWS instances with misconfigured WAFs. Capital One's ModSecurity WAF was vulnerable — either the WAF itself was SSRF-able, or a misconfiguration allowed reaching an SSRF-vulnerable application behind it.</p>
    <div class="r-steps">
      <strong>Attack reconstruction:</strong>
      <ol class="r-steps">
        <li>Thompson's scanner identifies Capital One's misconfigured WAF on AWS</li>
        <li>SSRF allows querying: <code>http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/</code></li>
        <li>Returns role name: <code>ISRM-WAF-Role</code></li>
        <li>Second request: <code>http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/ISRM-WAF-Role</code></li>
