  <h3>12.1 How Defenses Work (and How They Fail)</h3>

  <h4>Blacklist-Based Filtering (Always Broken)</h4>
  <p>Blocks specific strings like "127.0.0.1", "localhost", "169.254". Fails because the number of representations for any IP is essentially unbounded. Chapter 5 of this book documents dozens of bypasses — and that's far from complete.</p>

  <h4>Allowlist-Based Filtering (Better, Still Bypassable)</h4>
  <p>Only permits requests to specific approved destinations. Fails when: allowed domains have open redirects, URL parser inconsistencies allow confusion attacks, the allowlist is too broad (e.g., any subdomain of a large domain), or DNS rebinding is possible.</p>

  <h4>Network-Level Controls (Strongest)</h4>
  <p>Block outbound requests to RFC1918, loopback, and link-local ranges at the network layer. Requires egress filtering, VPC security groups, or iptables rules. Attackers must bypass this at the DNS/redirect level.</p>

  <h4>IMDSv2 (Cloud-Specific Mitigation)</h4>
  <p>AWS IMDSv2 requires a PUT request to get a session token, then that token must be included in all GET requests. Simple SSRF payloads that do GET-only requests can't get credentials. However, SSRF that can make PUT requests (e.g., via gopher://) can still chain IMDSv2.</p>

  <h3>12.2 Proper Mitigations (For Your Report's Recommendation)</h3>

  <pre><span class="c"># Application layer: use a maintained safe-URL library</span>
<span class="c"># Python:</span>
pip install requests-hardened  <span class="c"># Validates URLs against private IP ranges</span>

<span class="c"># Node.js:</span>
npm install ssrf-req-filter    <span class="c"># Rejects private IP requests</span>

<span class="c"># Java: Apache HttpClient with custom RoutePlanner
# Block all RFC1918 addresses: 10.*, 172.16-31.*, 192.168.*
# Block loopback: 127.*
# Block link-local: 169.254.*
# Block IPv6 loopback: ::1
# Block IPv6 link-local: fe80::/10

# Cloud-specific:
# AWS: Enforce IMDSv2 with PUT token requirement
aws ec2 modify-instance-metadata-options \
  --http-tokens required \        # Enforce IMDSv2
  --instance-id i-XXXXX

# Use least-privilege IAM roles
# The WAF role that caused the Capital One breach should have had ZERO S3 permissions</span></pre>

  <h3>12.3 Writing a Bug Report That Gets Paid</h3>

  <p>The difference between a $0 report and a $10,000 report is often just the quality of the write-up. Here's the proven structure:</p>

  <pre><span class="c"># REPORT TEMPLATE</span>

<span class="ok">## Title</span>
[CRITICAL] SSRF in [Feature Name] allows access to AWS instance metadata
and exfiltration of IAM credentials

<span class="ok">## Summary</span>
